>Hi-Point
Friends don't let friends buy Hi-Point products. PSA is decent, I have one of their AR uppers, but PSA doesn't make them out of cast zinc alloy.

Even in Current Year there are bargains to be had. There are police trade-in Glocks in .40 for under $300 if you look around. I am still seeing police trade-in S&W Model 10s in the $250 range, too, if you don't mind that they got issued to MPs on a base in Latin America, got corroded and pitted as fuck externally from humidity and salt air, badly enough that the reseller had some of them sandblasted and refinished in some kind of black powder coat. I wouldn't be shocked if they got frankenstein'd together out of non-matching parts, either, since a lot of refinishers and armorers doing a big batch will just dump all the sideplates in a box and do them all at once, all the frames, all the cylinders, etc., etc., and slap them back together without regard to which parts came from which. Collectors don't like that kind of thing, but if it works, hey, pinned-and-recessed pre-1980 Model 10 Barney Fife gun with the skinny barrel for two and a half bills. We no longer live in the era of the $59 SKS carbine, but there are still deals to be found.

And from a strictly utility perspective, unless hunting or trap or skeet or "sporting clays" is among your hobbies, you can skip over the shotgun. That PSA AR has a lot going for it as a tool for for home defense--thirty round mags, fast reloads, fast follow-up shots, and 5.56 terminal ballistics are impressive, even with oldschool M193 Ball.

I am currently obsessed with the idea of an old-fashioned side-by-side "coach gun" with external hammers, like you see in some old Western movies, but it'd be a toy I'd shoot occasionally at the range, not something I'd ever seriously contemplate for anything more serious than shooting paper targets. I already have an Italian Single Action Army clone in .357. It's just a range toy.

I shoot more .22 than all other calibers combined. I have a Ruger Mk III 22/45 and I stopped counting rounds through it at sixty thousand. For a while I worked near an indoor range and was shooting there after my shift, sometimes three bricks a week. I did eventually have to replace some of the springs. I'll be taking it to the range tomorrow. Would I go to war with it? No, but it's relatively inexpensive practice, it shoots to point of aim, though I did have to crank the rear sight all the way to the right, because the front sight is visibly canted (canted sights, they're not just for AKs) and it has a decent trigger. It's fun to shoot.

Small digression: it irks me when I hear people say "oh, yes, I have [.22 firearm] and I shoot it all the time, I've never had one malfunction with it! No, I've never even had a dud!" They must not shoot much. Some batches of Winchester and Remington bulk pack .22 have been 3-5% duds for me, in several different firearms, and some batches of Remington "Thunderbolts" have been over 10%, some of which would go off on a second try if I rotated the cartridge and tried again, some of which would not. I've gotten duds with every brand of .22 ammo out there, including CCI Mini-Mags, though I had to shoot a few thousand of those to get one. One of the current gun store memes is ".22 rimfire ammo is just as reliable as centerfire! don't believe the old wives' tales about duds!" Ha, no, horseshit. .22 LR M24 Ball made for the Second World War was corrosive primed and had really good QC and, back when it was cheap common surplus and not a collectors' item, yes people shot many thousands of them without failures. Between the wars, a guy named Ad Topperwein shot hundreds of thousands of rounds of Winchester .22 at public exhibitions, and only got four duds in a quarter million rounds, or so he claimed. Human hands and human eyes for QC were a thing then. They aren't now, not with the cheap bulk-pack .22. at Wal-Mart.
